com.facebook.collections

Class LongArray

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.facebook.collections.LongArray
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Array<Long>, Iterable<Long>

    @ThreadSafe
public class LongArray
extends Object
implements Array<Long>
    Reference implementation of SimpleArray using longs. Attempts to limit memory growth by allowing a small growth factor each resize

      • append

        public int append(Long value)
        Description copied from interface: Array
        add an element to the end of the array. Almost always shorthand for: 
        simpleArray.set(simpleArray.size(), value)
        (with an exception, see below) this is useful when you want to use the array like queue or stack, and in practice some one-off impls of classes like this did "append" only. with the difference that if size() == capacity(), the array it is automatically grown to accommodate the new value In the case if a value has been set past the "end" of contiguous values, this will continue and skip over set values and set the first empty value
        Specified by:
        append in interface Array<Long>
        Parameters:
        value - to add, may NOT be null
        Returns:
        position inserted at

      • resize

        public int resize(int sizeHint)
        Description copied from interface: Array
        the idea here is that want to grow the array, and give a 'hint'. Note, underlying implementations may not be able to create an array of the exact size For example, asking for 2 * size() might result in a slightly different size. For shrinking: one should copy to a smaller array. Because shrinking would have unknown effects on the indices of values known to the caller, there is not much value in having the ability to shrink internalized
        Specified by:
        resize in interface Array<Long>
        Parameters:
        sizeHint - can be thought of as a new size to grow to, but implementations may not grow to exactly that size. The actual size is returned. Should be > 0
        Returns:
        actual size of new array
